<div class="dablink">This article is about the sociological concept.  For the computer game, see <a href="/wiki/Bureaucracy_(computer_game)" title="Bureaucracy (computer game)" class="mw-redirect">Bureaucracy (computer game)</a>.  For the month, see <a href="/wiki/Discordian_calendar" title="Discordian calendar">Discordian calendar</a>.</div>
<p><b>Bureaucracy</b> is the structure and set of <a href="/wiki/Regulations" title="Regulations" class="mw-redirect">regulations</a> in place to control activity, usually in large organizations and government. As opposed to <a href="/wiki/Adhocracy" title="Adhocracy">adhocracy</a>, it is represented by standardized procedure (rule-following) that dictates the execution of most or all processes within the body, formal division of powers, hierarchy, and relationships. In practice the interpretation and execution of <a href="/wiki/Policy" title="Policy">policy</a> can lead to informal influence.</p>
